- 'tortoise in the race' refers to the idea of slow and steady, or in this context, consistently facing delays;
- 'top 3 most delayed flights' means the flights with the highest arrival delays for each month and year;
- 'average arrival delay' is calculated by summing the arrival delays and dividing by the number of flights.

- "troubled carriers" refers to airlines with the highest average delays;
- "heaviest burden of delays" refers to the total delay time caused by various factors, including late aircraft arrivals, carrier issues, weather, the National Airspace System, and security;
- "average minutes they keep passengers waiting" is calculated by averaging the total delay minutes for each carrier.

- 'Total arrival delay' is the cumulative delay time for all flights of a carrier;
- 'Average carrier delay' is the mean delay caused by the carrier for each flight;
- The results are ordered by the total number of flights, with the busiest airlines at the top.

- "significant delay issue" refers to an average arrival delay greater than 10 minutes;
- "on time" refers to flights with arrival delays of 15 minutes or less;
- The dataset includes at least 100 flights per carrier.

- "On-time arrival" is defined as a flight arriving within 15 minutes of its scheduled time;
- The on-time percentage is calculated by comparing the number of on-time arrivals to the total number of arrivals;
- The total delay minutes include delays caused by various factors such as the carrier, weather, NAS, security, and late aircraft.

- "Total arrival delay" is the sum of all positive arrival delays for a carrier;
- "Delayed flights" are those with an arrival delay greater than 0 minutes;
- "Top 10 carriers" refers to the carriers with the highest total delay.

- "Average arrival delay" is calculated by averaging the total arrival delay in minutes for each flight;
- "Flights in 2020" refers to the flights that were recorded in the year 2020;
- "More than 30 minutes" is a threshold used to filter out carriers with less significant delays.

- "delay rate" is the percentage of flights that were delayed;
- "cancellation rate" is the percentage of flights that were cancelled;
- "diversion rate" is the percentage of flights that were diverted.

- "Los Angeles International Airport" is a major airport in Los Angeles, California;
- "average delay" is calculated by averaging the total arrival delays for each carrier;
- "average delay > 10" means the average delay must be more than 10 minutes.

- Weather delays are delays caused by adverse weather conditions;
- NAS delays are delays caused by the National Airspace System, which includes air traffic control;
- Late aircraft delays are delays caused by the previous flight's late arrival.

sql:
SELECT ROUND(AVG(carrier_delay), 2) AS average_carrier_delay
FROM flights
WHERE carrier = 'UA' AND year = 2020 AND carrier_delay > 0;

SELECT MAX(total_flights) AS highest_number_of_flights
FROM (
  SELECT COUNT(flight_id) AS total_flights
  FROM flights
  GROUP BY year
) AS yearly_flights;
